<paragraph blockId="20.[138,1185,1629,1685]" lastBlockId="21.[125,1172,137,225]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="3970" pageId="20" pageNumber="3969">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Okada, 1977)" baseAuthorityName="Okada" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[467,802,1629,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Phortica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="3969" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eparmata">
<emphasis box="[467,609,1629,1652]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="3969">P. eparmata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Okada T" box="[633,794,1629,1653]" pageId="20" pageNumber="3969" pagination="17 - 31" refId="ref11977" refString="Okada T. 1977. The subgenus Phortica Schiner of the genus Amiota Loew of Japan and the Oriental Region, with reference to anti-Burla's rule (Diptera, Drosophilidae). Bulletin of the Biogeographical Society of Japan 32: 17 - 31." type="journal article" year="1977">Okada, 1977</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[889,976,1629,1653]" name="Taiwan" pageId="20" pageNumber="3969">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
in the shape of the aedeagal median rod, and having the anepisternum with setulae, but can be distinguished from the latter species by the arista and the shape of the paramere (in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Okada" baseAuthorityYear="1977" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Phortica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="3970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eparmata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="3970">P. eparmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: arista with five dorsal and one ventral branches, and paramere deeply concaved submedially).
</paragraph>
